4) Provider Configuration

provider "aws" {
  region = var.aws_region
}
Terraform needs a provider to communicate with AWS APIs.
Flow:

Terraform → AWS Provider → AWS API → Infrastructure
Example API calls Terraform makes:

CreateVpc
RunInstances
CreateLoadBalancer

5) Variables (Why They Are Important)

variable "aws_region" {}
variable "environment" {}
variable "instance_type" {}
Variables allow reusable infrastructure.
Without variables:

Hardcoded infrastructure
With variables:

Same code → different environments
Example environments:
Environment	Instance Type
dev	t3.micro
stage	t3.small
prod	t3.medium

6) Environment Files
Example:

dev.tfvars
stage.tfvars
prod.tfvars
Example file:

environment = "dev"
aws_region = "ap-south-1"
instance_type = "t3.micro"
Terraform loads these values during apply.
Command:

terraform apply -var-file=environments/dev.tfvars
Result:

Dev infrastructure created

7) VPC Module (Networking)
A VPC is your private cloud network.
Example:

resource "aws_vpc" "main" {
  cidr_block = "10.0.0.0/16"
}
CIDR explanation:

10.0.0.0/16
Range:

10.0.0.0 → 10.0.255.255
Total IPs:

65,536
Inside the VPC we create subnets:

Public subnet
Private subnet
Example:

10.0.1.0/24
10.0.2.0/24
Each subnet:

256 IP addresses

8) Internet Gateway
Purpose:
Allow internet communication.

VPC → Internet Gateway → Internet
Without IGW:

Instances cannot reach internet

9) NAT Gateway
Purpose:
Allow private instances to access internet.
Example use case:

EC2 installs updates
Pull Docker images
Flow:

Private EC2 → NAT → Internet

10) Security Groups (Firewall)
Example rule:

Allow HTTP (80)
Allow SSH (22)
Example:

ingress {
  from_port = 80
  to_port = 80
  protocol = "tcp"
  cidr_blocks = ["0.0.0.0/0"]
}
Meaning:

Anyone on internet can access port 80
Security groups act like:

Cloud firewall

11) EC2 Instances
Terraform creates compute servers.
Example:

resource "aws_instance" "app" {
  ami = "ami-xxxxx"
  instance_type = "t3.micro"
}
EC2 instance is where your app runs:

Node.js
Docker
Kubernetes
Web server

12) Application Load Balancer
Purpose:
Distribute traffic.
Without load balancer:

Internet → Single EC2
With load balancer:

Internet → ALB → Multiple EC2
Benefits:
	• high availability
	• traffic distribution
	• fault tolerance

13) Auto Scaling Group
Auto Scaling adjusts number of instances automatically.
Example rule:

CPU > 70% → add instance
CPU < 20% → remove instance
This provides:

Elastic scaling
Cost optimization

14) Terraform State (Very Important)
Terraform keeps track of infrastructure in a state file.
Example:

terraform.tfstate
State contains:

resource IDs
IP addresses
dependencies
Without state:
Terraform cannot manage infrastructure.

15) Remote State (S3)
Instead of local state:

local machine
We store state in S3.
Benefits:

team collaboration
state backup
CI/CD compatibility
Example backend:

backend "s3" {
  bucket = "terraform-state-project"
  key = "infra/terraform.tfstate"
  region = "ap-south-1"
}

16) DynamoDB Locking
Problem:
Two engineers run Terraform at same time.
Result:

State corruption
Solution:

DynamoDB state lock
Flow:

Terraform run
↓
Lock state
↓
Apply changes
↓
Unlock

