Result: AWS infrastructure created.

PHASE 2 — Install Docker on EC2
Goal: Run containerized applications.
On EC2 instance:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install docker.io -y
sudo systemctl start docker
sudo systemctl enable docker
Check Docker:

docker --version

PHASE 3 — Build Docker Application
Create a simple web application.
Example structure:

app
│
├ Dockerfile
├ index.html
└ nginx.conf
Example Dockerfile:

FROM nginx
COPY index.html /usr/share/nginx/html
Build image:

docker build -t devops-demo .
Run container:

docker run -d -p 80:80 devops-demo
Now your app runs inside Docker.

PHASE 4 — Kubernetes Cluster Setup
Goal: Manage containers at scale.
Cluster nodes:

1 Master node
2 Worker nodes
Install Kubernetes components:

kubeadm
kubelet
kubectl
Initialize cluster:

sudo kubeadm init
Join worker nodes:

kubeadm join <token>
Check nodes:

kubectl get nodes

PHASE 5 — Deploy Application to Kubernetes
Create deployment.
Example file:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: web-app
spec:
  replicas: 3
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: web
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: web
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: web
        image: devops-demo
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
Apply:

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
Check pods:

kubectl get pods

PHASE 6 — Expose Application
Create service.

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: web-service
spec:
  type: NodePort
  selector:
    app: web
  ports:
  - port: 80
    targetPort: 80
Apply:

kubectl apply -f service.yaml
Now application is accessible.

PHASE 7 — Add Monitoring
Install monitoring stack.
Monitoring tools:
	• Prometheus → collects metrics
	• Grafana → dashboards
Install using Helm:

helm install prometheus prometheus-community/kube-prometheus-stack
Access Grafana:

http://<node-ip>:3000
Metrics available:
	• CPU usage
	• Memory usage
	• Pod status
	• Node health

