Example output:

Terraform v1.x.x

Step 2 — Install AWS CLI
Download:
AWS CLI
Verify:

aws --version
Step-by-Step: Install AWS CLI on Windows (Using VS Code)
1️⃣ Download AWS CLI Installer
	1. Open this official download link:
https://awscli.amazonaws.com/AWSCLIV2.msi
	2. Download the file AWSCLIV2.msi.

2️⃣ Install AWS CLI
	1. Double-click AWSCLIV2.msi
	2. Click Next → Next → Install
	3. Click Finish
This installs AWS CLI and automatically adds it to Windows PATH.

3️⃣ Restart VS Code
If VS Code was already open:
	1. Close Visual Studio Code
	2. Open it again
This refreshes the environment variables.

4️⃣ Verify Installation in VS Code
	1. Open VS Code
	2. Open Terminal


aws --version

Step 3 — Create AWS Credentials
Go to Amazon Web Services Console
Navigate:

IAM → Users → Security Credentials → Access Keys
Create:

Access Key
Secret Key

Step 4 — Configure AWS CLI
Run:

aws configure
Enter:

AWS Access Key ID
AWS Secret Access Key
Region → ap-south-1
Output format → json
Test:

aws s3 ls
If no error appears → credentials are correct.

Step 5 — Create Project Folder
Open terminal and run:

mkdir terraform-phase1
cd terraform-phase1
Open this folder in **Visual Studio Code.

Step 6 — Create Terraform Files
Create these files:

terraform-phase1
│
├ provider.tf
├ main.tf
├ variables.tf
└ outputs.tf

Step 7 — Provider Configuration
Open provider.tf

provider "aws" {
  region = "ap-south-1"
}
This tells Terraform to use AWS Mumbai region.

Step 8 — Create VPC
Open main.tf
Add:

resource "aws_vpc" "main" {
  cidr_block = "10.0.0.0/16"

  tags = {
    Name = "devops-vpc"
  }
}
This creates your private network in AWS.

Step 9 — Create Subnet
Add below VPC:

resource "aws_subnet" "public_subnet" {
  vpc_id            = aws_vpc.main.id
  cidr_block        = "10.0.1.0/24"
  availability_zone = "ap-south-1a"

  tags = {
    Name = "public-subnet"
  }
}
This subnet will contain your EC2 instances.

Step 10 — Create Internet Gateway
Add:

resource "aws_internet_gateway" "igw" {
  vpc_id = aws_vpc.main.id

  tags = {
    Name = "devops-igw"
  }
}
Purpose: allow internet traffic.

Step 11 — Create Route Table
Add:

resource "aws_route_table" "public_rt" {
  vpc_id = aws_vpc.main.id

  route {
    cidr_block = "0.0.0.0/0"
    gateway_id = aws_internet_gateway.igw.id
  }

  tags = {
    Name = "public-route-table"
  }
}
This allows internet routing.

Step 12 — Associate Route Table with Subnet
Add:

resource "aws_route_table_association" "a" {
  subnet_id      = aws_subnet.public_subnet.id
  route_table_id = aws_route_table.public_rt.id
}
Now subnet can access internet.

Step 13 — Create Security Group
Add:

resource "aws_security_group" "web_sg" {
  vpc_id = aws_vpc.main.id

  ingress {
    from_port   = 22
    to_port     = 22
    protocol    = "tcp"
    cidr_blocks = ["0.0.0.0/0"]
  }

  ingress {
    from_port   = 80
    to_port     = 80
    protocol    = "tcp"
    cidr_blocks = ["0.0.0.0/0"]
  }

  egress {
    from_port   = 0
    to_port     = 0
    protocol    = "-1"
    cidr_blocks = ["0.0.0.0/0"]
  }
}
This allows:

SSH → port 22
HTTP → port 80

Step 14 — Launch EC2 Instance
Add:

resource "aws_instance" "server" {
  ami           = "ami-0f58b397bc5c1f2e8"
  instance_type = "t3.micro"

  subnet_id = aws_subnet.public_subnet.id

  vpc_security_group_ids = [
    aws_security_group.web_sg.id
  ]

  tags = {
    Name = "devops-server"
  }
}
This creates your server automatically.






