devops-end-to-end-project
│
├ terraform
├ docker
├ kubernetes
├ monitoring
Go inside terraform folder.

cd devops-end-to-end-project/terraform

Step 2 — Create Terraform Files
Create files:

touch provider.tf
touch variables.tf
touch main.tf
touch outputs.tf
Structure:

terraform
│
├ provider.tf
├ variables.tf
├ main.tf
└ outputs.tf

Step 3 — Configure Provider
Open provider.tf

provider "aws" {
  region = "ap-south-1"
}
This tells Terraform to use Mumbai region.

Step 4 — Create VPC
Open main.tf

resource "aws_vpc" "main" {
  cidr_block = "10.0.0.0/16"

  tags = {
    Name = "devops-vpc"
  }
}
Explanation:

10.0.0.0/16
Provides 65,536 IP addresses.

Step 5 — Create Public Subnet
Add below VPC.

resource "aws_subnet" "public_subnet" {
  vpc_id                  = aws_vpc.main.id
  cidr_block              = "10.0.1.0/24"
  availability_zone       = "ap-south-1a"
  map_public_ip_on_launch = true

  tags = {
    Name = "public-subnet"
  }
}
Public subnet allows internet access.

Step 6 — Create Private Subnet

resource "aws_subnet" "private_subnet" {
  vpc_id            = aws_vpc.main.id
  cidr_block        = "10.0.2.0/24"
  availability_zone = "ap-south-1a"

  tags = {
    Name = "private-subnet"
  }
}
Private subnet is not directly accessible from internet.

Step 7 — Create Internet Gateway

resource "aws_internet_gateway" "igw" {
  vpc_id = aws_vpc.main.id

  tags = {
    Name = "devops-igw"
  }
}
Purpose:
Allow VPC to connect to internet.

Step 8 — Create Elastic IP (for NAT)

resource "aws_eip" "nat_eip" {
  domain = "vpc"
}
Needed for NAT gateway.

Step 9 — Create NAT Gateway

resource "aws_nat_gateway" "nat" {
  allocation_id = aws_eip.nat_eip.id
  subnet_id     = aws_subnet.public_subnet.id

  tags = {
    Name = "devops-nat"
  }
}
Purpose:
Allow private subnet instances to access internet.
Example:

software updates
docker images
package downloads

Step 10 — Public Route Table

resource "aws_route_table" "public_rt" {
  vpc_id = aws_vpc.main.id

  route {
    cidr_block = "0.0.0.0/0"
    gateway_id = aws_internet_gateway.igw.id
  }

  tags = {
    Name = "public-route-table"
  }
}
Route:

0.0.0.0/0 → Internet Gateway

Step 11 — Private Route Table

resource "aws_route_table" "private_rt" {
  vpc_id = aws_vpc.main.id

  route {
    cidr_block     = "0.0.0.0/0"
    nat_gateway_id = aws_nat_gateway.nat.id
  }

  tags = {
    Name = "private-route-table"
  }
}
Route:

0.0.0.0/0 → NAT Gateway

Step 12 — Associate Public Route Table

resource "aws_route_table_association" "public_assoc" {
  subnet_id      = aws_subnet.public_subnet.id
  route_table_id = aws_route_table.public_rt.id
}

Step 13 — Associate Private Route Table

resource "aws_route_table_association" "private_assoc" {
  subnet_id      = aws_subnet.private_subnet.id
  route_table_id = aws_route_table.private_rt.id
}

Step 14 — Initialize Terraform
Run:

terraform init
This downloads the AWS provider.

Step 15 — Check Execution Plan

terraform plan
You should see resources like:

+ aws_vpc
+ aws_subnet
+ aws_nat_gateway
+ aws_internet_gateway
+ aws_route_table

Step 16 — Apply Infrastructure

terraform apply
Type:

yes
Terraform will create infrastructure in AWS.

Step 17 — Verify in AWS
Open **Amazon Web Services Console.
Check:

VPC
Subnets
Route Tables
NAT Gateway
Internet Gateway
All resources should appear.

